column80:
In the original study Two groups, A and B, heard read a list of character-qualities – Group A heard the person described as "warm"; Group B, as "cold." In this study the respondents read the list of “warm” or “cold” person qualities. 
 In the original study the respondents were instructed to select one quality/trait from each pair of 18 pairs in total. There were 17 pairs of traits in the replicated study.

column11: drunk utilitarian
column16: We revisited the "drunk utilitarian" phenomena which was indicated by Duke and Begue in 2015. Our study replicated the results of Francis et al., 2019, and Arutyunova et al., 2017 but we proposed more strict methodolody and more measures to study utilitarianism. We show that there is no such phenomena as "drunk utilitarian", people are not more utilitarian when they are under the influence of the alcohol.

predicts utilitarian responses in moral dilemmas. Cognition, 134, 121–127.

column16: The first effect that I entered regarding this reproduction study was wrongly labeled 'Effects of Smiling Emoticons on Virtual First Impressions (Smileys*Formality → Competence)' (the same as this one here). column80: One item was changed in wording ("Based on feedback from the pretest, minor linguistic adjustments were made (e.g., “. . . I manage to distance myself from my (work) tasks” instead of “. . . dis- tance myself from work”) to ensure that non-working individuals also feel addressed.) The SEM that we fitted did not exactly represent the one in original study. In the original study several items were deleted to achieve good model fit. However, this procedure was not outlined in the paper, and we could not get the exact model from the original authors. In the original study, participants were collected via the sosci panel and additionally via Facebook. In the replication, participants were collected via Facebook.

column80:
There are differences between this study and Greene and colleagues’ (2009). Firstly, Greene and colleagues conducted their study via pen and paper, whereas we used an online
 survey program completed at home. Original participants were from the United States, our participants were from Canada. Their participants were renumerated $3, ours entered into a raffle or awarded bonus points. 
 
 One notable difference between this study and Greene et al. is that each participant in our study responded to one footbridge dilemma and one speedboat dilemma with counterbalancing,
 creating a within-subject component. In Greene and colleagues’ study, Experiment 1a (footbridge) and Experiment 1b (speedboat) were conducted with separate participants. Our
 within-subjects approach to conducting Experiment 1a and 1b simultaneously maximized the data collected in a shorter timeframe. We also omitted the remote footbridge dilemma. The
 remote footbridge dilemma is similar to footbridge switch, except the agent is at a distance from the workman, eliminating spatial proximity. The planned contrast in Greene et al. (2009) that involved the remote footbridge dilemma (i.e., remote footbridge vs. footbridge switch to test the effect of physical proximity) was non-significant in the original study. Given the tight timeframe of data collection, we chose to omit this condition in this replication to maximize data collected for other conditions. Lastly, both studies screened for ‘suspended belief’ or ‘unconscious realism’ (when participants unconsciously replace unrealistic assumptions, portrayed by a moral dilemma, with more realistic ones). Both studies did this by asking participants whether they thought the action by the agent would result in the desired outcome. Participants provided an estimate (0-100%) as to whether the outcome would turn out as planned, turn out as worse, and turn out as better. Greene and colleagues used these estimates as covariates, while this study did not. Again, these covariates were all reported as nonsignificant in Greene et al. (2009), suggesting that they were unnecessary to add in the model.

column11: H1: The mean moral acceptability ratings will be higher in the footbridge switch condition when compared to the footbridge pole condition.
column12: Ratings of the moral acceptability of sacrificing one life to save five differed among the four dilemmas (F(3, 417) = 9.69, p < 0.0001). Planned pairwise contrasts revealed no significant effect of spatial proximity (remote footbridge vs. footbridge switch: F(1, 417) = 0.11 p = 0.74), no significant effect of physical contact (standard footbridge vs. footbridge pole: F(1, 417) = 1.43. p = 0.23), but a significant effect of personal force (footbridge switch vs. footbridge pole: F(1, 417) = 7.63, p = 0.006, d = 0.40; see Fig. 2).
column13: Ratings of the moral acceptability of sacrificing one life to save five differed among the four dilemmas (F(3, 417) = 9.69, p < 0.0001). Planned pairwise contrasts revealed no significant effect of spatial proximity (remote footbridge vs. footbridge switch: F(1, 417) = 0.11 p = 0.74), no significant effect of physical contact (standard footbridge vs. footbridge pole: F(1, 417) = 1.43. p = 0.23), but a significant effect of personal force (footbridge switch vs. footbridge pole: F(1, 417) = 7.63, p = 0.006, d = 0.40; see Fig. 2).

replication = Brouwer, A., Jin, X., Waldi, A. H., & Verheyen, S. (2021). Age biases the judgment rather than the perception of an ambiguous figure. Scientific Reports, 11, 8627. https://doi.org/10.1038/s41598-021-88139-1

column80:
- Instructions: Informed consent was adapted to the requirements of the university where the replication took place.
- Procedure: Prior to estimating the age of the ambiguous figure, participants indicated whether or not they had seen the figure before. After estimating the age, they performed additional tasks not included in the original study.
 
- Location: The original study was conducted on Mechanical Turk, while the replication was conducted on Prolific
- Participants populations: Participants in both studies were US adults, but there may exist differences between participants on Mechanical Turk and on Prolific. In the original study, the age groups were formed using a median split. In the replication study, two separate samples were recruited (one younger than the median from the original study and one older than the median from the original study).

column10: Freezing response to social threat
column11: Freezing is an adaptive defensive response to a stressful event. It is characterized by reduced body motion, reduced heart rate (bradycardia), and increased muscle tonus. Social threats in the context of these studies are stimuli of angry faces.
column16: "To conclude, the current research has largely replicated the freezing-to-social-threat effect initially demonstrated by Roelofs et al. (2010). We hope our work strengthens the confidence in the effect and paves the way for further research and applications in the context of (social) threat and physiology", but in a personal correspondence, Hilbert wrote that the results were ambiguous, thats why we decided to label it as an inconclusive result
column20: Among the effects reported in the original paper, only the effect on heart rate slowing (bradycardia) was tested in the replication study.
column26:
Roelofs, K., Hagenaars, M. A., & Stins, J. (2010). Facing freeze: Social
threat induces bodily freeze in humans. Psychological Science, 21, 1575–1581.
https://doi.org/10.1177/0956797610384746
column28: Roelofs, K., Hagenaars, M. A., & Stins, J. (2010). Facing freeze: Social threat induces bodily freeze in humans. Psychological Science, 21, 1575–1581. https://doi.org/10.1177/0956797610384746

column10: self-concept clarity, subscription services, self-signaling, retention choice, self-concept structure, identity signaling
column11: If you are uncertain about your own self-concept, then you will not want to introduce even more uncertainty by altering your identity. Consumers with “low self-concept clarity” should therefore be more motivated to keep their identities stable by (1) retaining products that are relevant to their identities, and (2) choosing not to acquire new products that are relevant to their identities.

column10: self-concept clarity, subscription services, self-signaling, retention choice, self-concept structure, identity signaling
column11: If you are uncertain about your own self-concept, then you will not want to introduce even more uncertainty by altering your identity. Consumers with “low self-concept clarity” should therefore be more motivated to keep their identities stable by (1) retaining products that are relevant to their identities, and (2) choosing not to acquire new products that are relevant to their identities.

column16: Crucially, in the replication only the "FB1" condition was replicated, which is prone to alternative explanations, while the "FB2" condition, which exlcudes alternative explanations showed effects in the opposite direction to the original study.

column32: Kulke, L., Von Duhn, B., Schneider, D., & Rakoczy, H. (2018). Is implicit theory of mind a real and robust phenomenon? results from a systematic replication study. Psychological Science, 29(6), 888–900. https://doi.org/10.1177/0956797617747090
column62: Kulke, L., von Duhn, B., Schneider, D., & Rakoczy, H. (2018). Is implicit theory of mind a real and robust phenomenon? Results from a systematic replication study. Psychological science, 29(6), 888-900., p.893
column80:
The replication tested adults instead of the toddlers tested in the original study, as the original and later studies suggest that the effect is consistent across the life span. The replication included four different paradigms which were tested within participants, while the original only included one paradigm. The replication computed the same eye movement measures but used the Differential Looking Score (DLS) as suggested in a later study by the original authors (Senju et al., 2009); therefore, the used statistics differ. The replication tested German participants, instead of British participants. The authors of the original study provided the original stimuli for the replication. One author of a different original Theory of Mind paradigm is also a co-author on the replication. 
 Crucially, in the replication only the "FB1" condition was replicated, which is prone to alternative explanations, while the "FB2" condition, which exlcudes alternative explanations showed effects in the opposite direction to the original study.

 NB. Both studie were ANOVAs so several test statistics were reported. However, given that this is a ranomised experiment with a treatment condition and a control condition I decided that the most appopriate statistical test to report is the t-test comparing the two groups after the treatment has been applied.
column80:
Original was lab-based and recurited UK undergrad students. Replication was online and recurited from a UK pool. 
 
 Original doesn't appear to involve any remuneration (although this isn't specificaly stated). Replicatication involved payment.
 
 Original doesn't appear to have any participant exclusions (although this isn't specifically stated). Replication excluded participants who failed quality checks.

 Vaughn's (2019) Study 2 Samples 1 and 2 had the same procedure through the measure of need satisfaction except that Sample 2 had a self-esteem measure on a page between where the participants wrote their description and the page containing the measure of need satisfaction.
 
 Otherwise, the procedures of Vaughn's (2017) Studies 1a-1c and Vaughn's (2019) Study 2 Samples 1 and 2 were the same through the page containing the measure of need satisfaction.

column62: All of the reported data (sample sizes and effect sizes) are visible in the abstract of the replication paper, Lopez et al., 2023, p. 1. It reports both the original and replication sample and effect sizes.
column80: There were no obvious relevant differences between the original and replication study. They possibly differ in exclusion criteria and nationality of the respondents. But it is impossible to tell since these issues are not described in the original study.
